column608: This is one of the oldest temples of Odisha. Lord Vishnu worshiped as Nilamadhaba. The name itself describes Lord Krishna. Nila means dusky (dark color) and Madhab is another name of Shree Krishna. This temple is situated near the riverbank of Mahanadi in kantilo, Odisha. Lord Nilamadhaba occupies a prominent position in the cult of Lord Jagannath. This temple is a miniature of the current Lord Jagannath temple Puri and also has similar rules and rituals. This temple is 100 km away from Bhubaneswar. There are lots of other temples around this temple.

column608:
If you choose to be in Phulbani and keen visit a waterfall...You have many options...The best is undoubtedly the Katramal. But it is risky and the approach roads are not at all good. Further if you happen to be with family or small kids... Then the safest bet is to visit Urmagarh Waterfall...It provides the same enthralling and mesmerizing feeling and it is safe even for kids... Besides the approach roads are superb and you literally don't go on a rollercoaster ride as with the other waterfalls nearby...This is a great picnic spot and like every other place in Phulbani...You can literally breathe fresh air everywhere...Most importantly there is a great park adjacent to it... it's just not a makeover park but a proper park...So kids can spend hours enjoying themselves while you are busy cooking for your picnic party...❣️😍🥰👌😊🤩👍♥️

Urmagarh waterfall is named after Urma Devi who is considered as the key goddess of the local tribes and it is believed that nobody can escape from this deity by saying a lie or giving a false statement. Thus she becomes the witness for truth and faith...🙏❣️😍🥰👌😊🤩👍♥️🙏

Here is a brief overview of the different waterfalls collected from various sources:-
Phulbani has an average elevation of 485 metres (1591 feet). It is located 211 km from Bhubaneshwar, the capital of Odisha and 165 km from Berhampur, the major city of South Odisha. Nearest railway station is Rairakhol around 100 km from here. The region around Phulbani has a variety of flora and fauna. It is a place surrounded by hills and has a lot of small and big waterfalls around it. Katramal Waterfall, the most spectacular of the lot is situated at a distance of about 31 km from Phulbani. Putudi Waterfall, a hot spot among the local people is situated at a distance of about 18 km from Phulbani. Pakdajhar waterfall is situated at a distance of about 3–5 km from Sudrukumpa, a small village which is situated about 19 km from the main city of Phulbani. Last but not the least, there is Urmagarh waterfall, which is close to 21 km from Phulbani. Phulbani is surrounded by River Salunki...❣️😍🥰👌😊🤩👍♥️💞

A must visit when you're visiting Ghatagaon Tarini Temple, it's around 15 km from the Temple.

A beautiful tourist fascinating place, where there's
• enough place for parking cars/bus/etc.
• enough space for feasts and all.
• beautiful spots here and there for capturing pictures.
• steps are made by PWD Dept. and railings have been made to go down the water to click pictures/bath, etc.
• various stalls are there by the Adivasi villagers, where they sell fresh vegetables and their traditional drink "Handia"
• various shops as in recreational stuffs for attracting children are there too.

Over-all, it's a beautiful place to visit if you are attracted to waterfalls, if not, also, must give this place a visit.

‼️What Not To Do‼️
▪︎The water is deep, so be careful while taking pictures, do not go near to the fall.
▪︎ The rocks during rainy season become slippery, so please avoid going and standing there, there are chances of slipping.
▪︎ There is a bridge there, don't go to the edge of it.

Take safety measures, enjoy the place.

column608:
Pushpagiri (Odia: ପୁଷ୍ପଗିରି) was an ancient Indian mahavihara or monastic complex located atop Langudi Hill (or Hills) in Jajpur district of Odisha, India. Pushpagiri was mentioned in the writings of the Chinese traveller Xuanzang (c. 602 – c. 664) and some other ancient sources. Until the 1990s, it was hypothesised to be one or all of the Lalitgiri-Ratnagiri-Udayagiri group of monastic sites, also located in Jajpur district. These sites contain ruins of many buildings, stupas of various sizes, sculptures (many now removed to museums), and other artifacts.

However, archaeological excavations conducted at Langudi Hills during 1996-2006 resulted in the discovery of another site, with inscriptions describing the local monastery as puṣpa sabhar giriya, and identified by the excavators as Pushpagiri. This has now become the general view among scholars. The site has now been made accessible for tourism.

The visit of Xuanzang indicates that Pushpagiri was an important Buddhist site in ancient India. Along with Nalanda, Vikramashila, Odantapuri, Takshashila and Vallabhi, it is believed to be a major ancient centre of learning. It flourished between 3rd and 11th centuries CE

column608:
Satapada is a town in Puri district, Odisha, India. In Odia sata means "seven" and pada means "village", so Satapada means group of seven villages. It is located 50 kilometers from Puri. Satapada on Chilika is home to the Irrawaddy dolphin.

Satapada is located at 19°40'10"N and 85°26'38"E. It is located on the southern part of the Chilika Lake near to village Panasapada which is 36 km from puri. Satapada is also for Sea Mouth Island where Chilika Lake meets the Bay of Bengal.

Air: The nearest airport is Biju Patnaik Airport at Bhubaneswar, around 120 km away.

Rail: Nearest rail head is at Puri, around 50 km away. Puri connects to all the major places in the country via superfast and express trains.

Road: National Highway 203A connects Satpada to Puri, 49 km away. Bhubaneshwar and Puri have daily bus services along with taxis to Satapada. Conducted tours are also organised by OTDC and local tour operators.

Satpada is located at the northeast cape of Chilika Lake and Bay of Bengal. The famous Chilika dolphins can be seen in their natural best here. There are also ample opportunities for canoeing, kayaking and boating. A small island called Rajahamsa is situated near this place at the mouth of the lagoon. It is named after the rajahamsa (mute swan). This island is 18 kilometers from Satapada. Rajahans is a small strip of land of which one side is placed near the lagoon and the other side is towards the Bay of Bengal.

Migratory birds do not visit Satapada very often, but a few varieties of migratory birds move to Nalabana bird sanctuary. It takes around four hours by boat from Satapada to reach Nalaban.

The temple is built in circular fashion housing 64 Yoginis in their different avatars. Each having a unique hairstyle n riding on its own vahan (vehicle). U will see female version of Ganpati n Nrusinh as well. The pandas will give good background of the temples n it's origin. Most of these idols are damaged by Mughals but still are able to convey the everlasting hindu philosophy n cultural heritage. The lawns surrounding the temple is beautifully maintained n looks very serene. There is a modest government guest house next to the temple where I assume rooms are made available. A spiritual person will find the place very close to heart but those who are not should enjoy it as one more heritage monument with touch of our great hindu culture .....

column608:
Udayagiri in Jajpur district is the largest Buddhist complex in Odisha. It is composed of major stupas and monasteries viharas. Together with the nearby complexes of Lalitgiri and Ratnagiri, it is part of the "Diamond Triangle of Odisha.

Located in the foothills, around 90 kilometres from Bhubaneswar. The ruins are beautiful and tells us a lot of history. One can see various sculptures of Buddha and other deities. The courtyard where monks used to come and stay for a short period is very interesting. There is a small stepwell also.

It is not very hilly but maybe difficult for older people to move around as it’s spread over a large area.

Putudi waterfall, Phulbani Putudi is a place of natural beauty where river Salunki falls from the height of 60ft. forming an enchanting ambience. The roaring sound of the fall with dense forest all around creates a thrilling sensation. It is 18 kms from Phulbani town.

Best to go for this place by bike ride. The road is very bad, it is not good to take your car, No repair work is happening too. Many places the roads are so narrow that only one car can pass through. If car comes from opposite side, then it will be a nightmare. Take experienced drivers only.
Anyway, the place is Beautiful...👌👌👌
